{
  "text": "In the final step, the vehicle state estimation, a Kalman Filter (KF), extended Kalman filter (EKF) or Unscented Kalman Filter (UKF) is commonly applied. In [CITATION_1] , a single vehicle state model with KF has been applied to vehicle tracking using low-cost LIDAR. In [CITATION_2] , the Independent Steered Model (ISM) and Variable-Axis Ackerman Steered Model (VASM) have been combined with KF to predict the state of the moving vehicle in each frame. In [CITATION_3] , moving vehicles can be detected as the outliers of ICP methods, with EKF applied to estimate the non-linear state of each vehicle. All these methods are based on the assumption that the vehicle model and the co-variance of the environment, which might be inaccessible, are well known. Instead of using the three-step tracking framework, other types of techniques are also proposed. In [CITATION_4] , a particle filter-based method is used which directly tracks the vehicles without the need of the data segmentation and association steps. However, how to improve the speed and efficiency of this family of methods is still an open problem. In this paper, we apply the multiple model association (MMA) algorithm, which considers the co-variance of pre-fit residual error to select the best vehicle model and KF parameter setting. It eliminates the effect of the inaccuracy caused by the assumption of single-vehicle models, without dramatically increasing the computation complexity.",
